This salad was a great hit. Here's yet another variation. When I went to make it, I realised that my jar of 'couscous' was actually bulghur wheat. Just use a little more water to cook the bulgar in.

Rating: 3
I made this recipe using all kinds of substitutions and it turned out great. I substituted roasted garlic for the regular garlic, roasted garlic olive oil, fresh oregano for the mint, and fresh Italian parsley for the arugula. Kalamata or nicoise olives would make a nice addition. I took it to a BBQ and everyone went back for seconds.

Rating: 4
This recipe is a refreshing accompaniment to broiled chicken or pork. I adapted it to the lactose intollerent crowd by adding color and roasted garlic instead of cheese. Just substitute bright orange lentils (5 min. cook time)for the green or brown, finely chopped parsley instead of arugula, and roasted garlic (instead of raw--it gives it a sweet and mellow garlic flavor).

Rating: 3
This is just the kind of healthy, delicious recipe I love. If you are a lentil and couscous lover, you'll really like the way these are presented here.

Rating: 4
This is my favorite salad recipe - I bring it to all potlucks and even used it when catering a friend's wedding. It scales up well - I've prepared up to 6 batches at once. Prepare some extra to keep at home, and bring copies of the recipe with you. It' perfect as is, but you can play with herbs a bit (basil for the mint) depending on what you have on hand.